			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="index.html#comment-61996">
				December 31, 2013 at 09:23					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>John:</p>
<p>Early in The Hugo Awards&#8217; evolution, there were no technical definitions for terms such as &#8220;Novel.&#8221; The <a href="http://www.smofs.org/cons1963.htm" title="1963 WSFS Consitution" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">1963 version of the WSFS Constitution</a>, for example, merely defined &#8220;Short Fiction&#8221; as &#8220;less than novel length,&#8221; and did not define what &#8220;novel length&#8221; was. Therefore, any work that wasn&#8217;t a &#8220;Novel&#8221; would have been classified as &#8220;Short Fiction,&#8221; including novella-length works until the written-fiction categories were subdivided and more technically defined.</p>
</div>

				<div class="reply">
				<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='index.html?replytocom=61996#respond' data-commentid="61996" data-postid="11" data-belowelement="comment-61996" data-respondelement="respond" aria-label='Reply to Kevin'>Reply</a>				</div><!-- .reply -->
